article.abstract:
<jats:sec sec-type="subject">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Subject</jats:title>
               <jats:p>China's trade in services.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="significance">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Significance</jats:title>
               <jats:p>The 13th Five-Year Plan ratified by the National People's Congress in March sets a target of increasing the service sector's share of China's foreign trade to 16%. At the beginning of the 21st century China was a marginal player in the global market for commercial services; today it is among the top five services exporters.  The government is promoting service exports and has set an ambitious 1-trillion-dollar target for 2020 -- more than four times the 2014 figure of 232.5 billion dollars. However, China's trade in services is permanently in deficit and its services imports are expanding much faster than exports. It has become the largest net importer of services in the world.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="impacts">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Impacts</jats:title>
               <jats:p>In the foreseeable future, China is likely to become the world's largest importer of services, overtaking the United States.</jats:p>
               <jats:p>A growing number of Chinese service companies will become household names around the world, especially in the developing countries.</jats:p>
               <jats:p>China's services trade deficit will partly offset its merchandise trade surplus, reducing overall trade imbalances with Western partners.</jats:p>
               <jats:p>Chinese import demand will grow in transportation, tourism, finance, telecommunications, consulting, legal services and education.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
title: China will 'rise' in global services market
container-title: Emerald Expert Briefings

article.abstract:
<jats:sec sec-type="subject">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Subject</jats:title>
               <jats:p>China's services sector.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="significance">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Significance</jats:title>
               <jats:p>Preliminary economic data for the first quarter of 2016 show that a buoyant service sector helped minimise the negative impact on GDP growth resulting from China's industrial slowdown, with services growing 7.6% compared with overall GDP growth of 6.9%. A key question is to what extent services will be able to maintain this supportive role, given the many challenges that face their continued expansion.  </jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="impacts">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Impacts</jats:title>
               <jats:p>The importance of exports as a driver of economic growth will recede with the shift from manufacturing to services.</jats:p>
               <jats:p>Import demand growth will weaken, as services require less energy, fewer raw materials and fewer intermediate goods than industry.</jats:p>
               <jats:p>The combined import and export effect will dampen China's impact on the world economy and dampen global commodity demand. </jats:p>
               <jats:p>Buoyant service sector growth will, however, encourage greater foreign direct investment in services. </jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
title: Services sector holds hope for China's economy
container-title: Emerald Expert Briefings

article.abstract:
<jats:sec sec-type="subject">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Subject</jats:title>
               <jats:p>Outlook for app-based services such as Uber in Indonesia.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="significance">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Significance</jats:title>
               <jats:p>Uber started its business in Indonesia in 2014, and is now operating in four major urban areas: Jakarta, Bandung, Surabaya and Bali. There are many other app-based transportation and other services operating in Indonesia, but Uber's presence in particular has led to major protests by taxi drivers in Jakarta and Bali. </jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="impacts">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Impacts</jats:title>
               <jats:p>Absent an MRT system in Indonesia's large cities, middle-class consumers will be drawn to app-based taxi services.</jats:p>
               <jats:p>Innovation in app-based transportation and other services will lead conventional businesses to adapt to ensure survival.</jats:p>
               <jats:p>Taxi services are no panacea for Indonesia's vast transport gap; the government will seek foreign investment to expand services.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
title: Indonesian policy set to boost app-based services

article.abstract:
<jats:sec sec-type="subject">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Subject</jats:title>
               <jats:p>Expansion of fintech in South-east Asia.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="significance">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Significance</jats:title>
               <jats:p>South-east Asia is primed for a rapid expansion of financial technology ('fintech'), despite a lack of both digital infrastructure and region-wide regulation. The region is seeing growing demand for electronic payments.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="impacts">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Impacts</jats:title>
               <jats:p>As fintech develops across South-east Asia, acquisitions of smaller local companies by large players will increase.</jats:p>
               <jats:p>In many local markets, foreign companies will be forced to rely on local fintech providers.</jats:p>
               <jats:p>New regulations could provide opportunities for new forms of digital protectionism.</jats:p>

               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Subject</jats:title>
               <jats:p>Business models of encrypted communication services.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="significance">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Significance</jats:title>
               <jats:p>Founded in 2009 on principles of security and privacy, WhatsApp has become one of the most popular means of digital communication on the planet. It has 1.2 billion monthly active users, up from 450 million in 2014 -- but no revenue. </jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="impacts">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Impacts</jats:title>
               <jats:p> Users will balance the privacy gains and monetary cost of using encrypted platforms. </jats:p>
               <jats:p> Faced with hate speech on encrypted services, government pressure is rising for increasing law enforcement access to such services.</jats:p>
               <jats:p> Resistance from employees of large technology firms over privacy will dictate changes to products as much as market forces or legislation. </jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
title: Encrypted digital services weigh viability and privacy

               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Subject</jats:title>
               <jats:p>IoT ecosystem.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="significance">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Significance</jats:title>
               <jats:p>The market for the Internet of Things (IoT) or connected devices is expanding rapidly, with no manufacturer currently forecast to dominate the supply chain. This has fragmented the emerging IoT ecosystem, triggering questions about interoperability and cybersecurity of IoT devices.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="impacts">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Impacts</jats:title>
               <jats:p> Firms in manufacturing, transportation and logistics and utilities are expected to see the highest IoT spending in coming years. </jats:p>
               <jats:p> The pace of IoT adoption is inextricably linked to that of related technologies such as 5G, artificial intelligence and cloud computing. </jats:p>
               <jats:p> Data privacy and security will be the greatest constraint to IoT adoption.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>

article.abstract:
<jats:sec sec-type="subject">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Subject</jats:title>
               <jats:p>Services trade outlook.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="significance">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Significance</jats:title>
               <jats:p>Trade in services is growing faster than trade in goods, and has the potential to drive growth in world trade overall. The WTO's 2019 World Trade report this month raises awareness that barriers are higher in services than in goods trade and attempts to draw policy attention to this. However, the intangible nature of services and the opaque nature of the political and regulatory barriers makes the sector more vulnerable than goods to rising protectionism. Indeed, the WTO services barometer suggests that the immediate outlook for services trade is weakening. </jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="impacts">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Impacts</jats:title>
               <jats:p>Services trade is outpacing goods but gets less attention, even though retaliation against US tariffs may cut the US services surplus.</jats:p>
               <jats:p>Compatible and interoperable cross-border regulation will cut services trade costs, but the US-China dispute is raising services barriers. </jats:p>
               <jats:p>Lower entry barriers in services, especially for small firms, should cut inequality, but firms clustering might raise regional inequality.</jats:p>
               <jats:p>Climate change will transform the 1-trillion-dollar tourism sector.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
title: Digitalisation will drive cross-border services trade

               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Subject</jats:title>
               <jats:p>The environmental politics of artificial island-building in the South China Sea.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="significance">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Significance</jats:title>
               <jats:p>Recent satellite photography has illustrated China's land reclamation and island-building work in the disputed Spratly islands in the South China Sea. Artificial island-building is likely to facilitate increases in the permanent population of the area. This raises the question of island-building's environmental, social and industrial implications.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="impacts">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Impacts</jats:title>
               <jats:p>Extracting any South China Sea oil and gas reserves could damage maritime ecology further.</jats:p>
               <jats:p>If artificial island populations grow, waste management could become a problem.</jats:p>
               <jats:p>Mutual need to protect fishing stocks could provide an avenue for multilateral discussion on maritime disputes.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>

article.abstract:
<jats:sec sec-type="subject">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Subject</jats:title>
               <jats:p>UK financial industry's 'passporting' and 'equivalence' in post-Brexit EU. </jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="significance">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Significance</jats:title>
               <jats:p>Under current EU rules, the United Kingdom will lose its passporting rights -- which allow financial companies authorised in the United Kingdom to sell their products across the European Economic Area (EEA) -- once it leaves the bloc. This would damage the reputation and status of the City of London as Europe’s leading financial centre. </jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="impacts">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Impacts</jats:title>
               <jats:p>The EU is unlikely to change its tough stance and allow the United Kingdom to retain its passporting rights after its leaves the EEA. </jats:p>
               <jats:p>Cities in remaining EU member states such as Dublin, Frankfurt or Paris may attract some business from London.  </jats:p>
               <jats:p>However, New York will probably be the biggest winner in the long term. </jats:p>
               <jats:p>Restrictions on EU migration could further impact the competitiveness and attractiveness of the City of London after Brexit. </jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
title: Brexit is set to weaken UK financial services industry

article.abstract:
<jats:sec sec-type="significance">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Significance</jats:title>
               <jats:p>Technology firms warn that building such a ‘backdoor’ would weaken encryption and security for all users and erode privacy.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="impacts">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Impacts</jats:title>
               <jats:p> Data breaches by criminal actors could increase if encryption is weakened.</jats:p>
               <jats:p> Criminal activity is constantly shifting to services that offer end-to-end encryption.</jats:p>
               <jats:p> Facebook's WhatsApp, which dominates the global messaging market, would be worst affected by changes in encryption rules.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>

article.abstract:
<jats:sec sec-type="significance">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Significance</jats:title>
               <jats:p>Even if it succeeds, this will have a greater disruptive impact on the trade in services than goods, because the EU’s single market enables greater cross-border services trade than is typical of other free trade agreements (FTAs). This is likely to cut the volume of EU-UK services trade, in which the United Kingdom currently enjoys a substantial surplus.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="impacts">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Impacts</jats:title>
               <jats:p>The United Kingdom’s departure from the EU will diminish its appeal for multinationals over the next few years, at least. </jats:p>
               <jats:p>The new UK immigration system could result in staff shortages in low-skilled services sectors. </jats:p>
               <jats:p>The imperative of tackling COVID-19 will likely delay the conclusion of new trade deals with non-EU countries.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
title: Brexit will be damaging for UK-EU services trade

article.abstract:
<jats:sec sec-type="significance">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Significance</jats:title>
               <jats:p>Such expectations will be difficult to meet because of the financial constraints imposed by debt accumulated to fight the pandemic and address its economic consequences. Many governments will seek to leverage artificial intelligence (AI) and cloud computing-based solutions to meet new needs.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="impacts">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Impacts</jats:title>
               <jats:p> Cybersecurity spending could add pressure on public debt loads.</jats:p>
               <jats:p> More developing countries will adopt data protection legislation, but enforcement will be patchy.</jats:p>
               <jats:p> The privatisation of government data may harm developing-country open data initiatives.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>

article.abstract:
<jats:sec sec-type="significance">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Significance</jats:title>
               <jats:p>Its two key attributes -- flexible scale and access from anywhere -- make it a perfect fit for governments, non-profits and commercial firms needing to launch new services, and they accommodate remote working and distance learning. </jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
            <jats:sec sec-type="impacts">
               <jats:title content-type="abstract-subheading">Impacts</jats:title>
               <jats:p> The pandemic will strain the traditional data-centre economy as uses for self-hosted computing diminish.</jats:p>
               <jats:p> Cloud services will be central to the expansion of digital health services.</jats:p>
               <jats:p> Large cloud providers will maintain their market dominance partly due to their stronger cybersecurity capabilities.</jats:p>
            </jats:sec>
title: Cloud services face new scrutiny as industry matures
